body:
Below is the problematic code `test.v`:

```verilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps
module qfhclxakch(in1, clock_0, clock_2, out99);
  input wire [1:0] in1;
  input wire clock_0;
  input wire clock_2;
  output wire [27:14] out99;
  wire [8:0] _133_;
  reg [21:0] reg_1;

  initial begin
    reg_1 = 22'h000000;
  end

  assign _133_ = in1[1] ? { 8'h00, in1[0] } : reg_1[13:4];
  assign out99 = reg_1[13:0];

  always @(negedge clock_0, posedge clock_2)
    if (clock_2) reg_1 <= 22'h0003cb;
    else reg_1 <= { reg_1[21:13], _133_, reg_1[3:0] };

endmodule
```

And the corresponding testbench file `tb.v`:

```verilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps
module tb_qfhclxakch;

  reg  [1:0] in1;
  reg        clock_0;
  reg        clock_2;
  wire [27:14] out99;

  qfhclxakch dut (
      .in1     (in1),
      .clock_0 (clock_0),
      .clock_2 (clock_2),
      .out99   (out99)
  );

  initial begin
    {in1, clock_0, clock_2} = 0;
    #2000;
    $display("reg1: %b", dut.reg_1);

    $finish;
  end
endmodule
```

The following commands reproduce the issue:

```
iverilog test.v tb.v 
./a.out
```

iverilog produces the following output:

```
reg1: 000000000xxxxxxxxx0000
tb.v:21: $finish called at 2000000 (1ps)
```

It can be seen that the initialization of `reg_1` in `test.v` is only partially effective, as the bits in the \[12:4] range are initialized to `x`. I suspect the issue is related to the line `reg_1 <= { reg_1[21:13], _133_, reg_1[3:0] };`, since `_133_` corresponds to that range. I'm not sure whether this behavior is expected.

